<br>
Art, you have become our comforting Soul,<br><br>
Talk Rising above survivor's guilt, I have here enclosed a portion of a letter I once received when I first started reaching out to find the Marines I had served with in Vietnam. The letter was send to me last November by a fellow Machine gunner who was wounded and I hope to see again in a couple of weeks. We haven't seen each other since that time.<br><br>
November 23, 1996<br>
Dear cookie:<br><br>
To say that I was surprised when you called three weeks ago would be an understatement. Twenty-nine years ago on this date I was in the hospital at Cameron Bay after being wounded on Operation Foster. You were in the mist of a battle at Phu Binh 1 trying to survive the day. When I was medevacked on November 19th I remember looking down at the battlefield from the helicopter watching tracer rounds illuminate the twilight and wondered what would become of all the Marines in India Company. I was very pleased to learn from you that most did survive and went on to lead productive lives. After I left, my memories laid mostly dormant for many years. Occasionally I would over hear a conversation that would cause me to think back and once in awhile I would have a fleeting thought of places and people that I served with, but mostly went on with my life. Like you, I hardly ever talked with anyone about Viet Nam to any degree because most did not understand the intensity of our feelings and could not fathom the underlying emotion that we all had. I certainly never expected to contact anyone from India Company but was pleased when you called and totally overcome with the memories and the pride that we all feel. It is reinforcing to know that all you guys still remember. <br><br>
This Marine when I spoke to him, I found out felt guilty for having been medivacked; He had been wounded but still felt guilty for leaving us while we were in the midst of a battle.  There were others I have found who felt guilty for having been send on a chow run, to get re-supplies, were on R&amp;R when the unit got hit and suffered heavy casualties or any number of other things that happened and they were not there. They survived. <br>
The survivor's guilt complex, I guess has cast its shadow over all of us. I have spoken to Marines who were ripped from the fields of battle and then send to a hospital ship or other medical facility and eventually discharged from service and they never knew what happened to the others and have felt guilty ever since.  Perhaps that was why, when you flight date came in and you were send to the rear you didn't hesitate or even took time to say good-by, you just quickly packed your gear and were gone. <br><br>

